## Teaching Back – Linux File Permissions

Linux file permissions control who can read, write, or execute a file. Every file has three types of users: the owner, the group, and others. Permissions are represented by numbers such as 7, 5, and 4. For example, `chmod 755 script.sh` gives the owner full permissions (read, write, execute) while the group and others can only read and execute the file. This system helps protect files from unauthorized access. System administrators use permissions to control what users can do on a system. Understanding permissions is important for managing security and running scripts safely in Linux.


